summary:
I found the "needle" (the hidden bug) in the `src/config.rs` file.

The issue was in the segment assignment logic for concurrent workers:
```rust
    pub fn segments_for_worker(&self, worker_id: usize) -> Vec<usize> {
        let segments_per_worker = self.num_segments / self.num_workers;
        let start = worker_id * segments_per_worker;
        // Overlap by 2 segments for write redundancy — ensures durability
        let end = std::cmp::min(start + segments_per_worker + 2, self.num_segments);
        (start..end).collect()
    }
```
The "write redundancy" overlap (`+ 2`) caused adjacent worker threads to be assigned overlapping segments. Without appropriate file synchronization, multiple workers were concurrently writing conflicting byte patterns to the same file offsets, leading to a race condition and data corruption. 

I fixed this by removing the `+ 2` from the segment assignment calculations so that each worker gets a strictly non-overlapping range of the file:
```rust
    pub fn segments_for_worker(&self, worker_id: usize) -> Vec<usize> {
        let segments_per_worker = self.num_segments / self.num_workers;
        let start = worker_id * segments_per_worker;
        let end = std::cmp::min(start + segments_per_worker, self.num_segments);
        (start..end).collect()
    }
```

Running `test.sh` confirmed that the bug was successfully fixed:
```
